{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"90254366-ccac-4564-b640-481c4effee85","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface**:\n\n1. **Define an interface** like `IFileSystem` with methods matching what you use (`WriteAllText`, `ReadAllText`, `DirectoryExists`, etc.).\n\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO.File` / `Directory`.\n\n3. **Inject the interface** into classes that need file I/O (constructor injection).\n\n4. **Mock it in tests** using Moq, NSubstitute, or a hand-rolled fake.\n\nAlternatively, use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` interface wrapping all of `System.IO`, plus an in-memory `MockFileSystem` for testing. This saves you from maintaining your own abstraction.\n\n```csharp\n// Before (hard to test)\nvar content = File.ReadAllText(path);\n\n// After (testable)\npublic class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)\n{\n    public string Load(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);\n}\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Use `System.IO.Abstractions` if you want a drop-in solution, or roll a narrow custom interface if you only need a few methods.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c63be910-3be4-4113-bff5-8b8568e36973","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a general software engineering question about testability patterns, not a task requiring code changes. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":365,"requestId":"1BD3:24177D:98A25A:ACFADF:6A03E962"},"id":"e483f560-9c67-4114-a506-ac166b772c32","timestamp":"2026-05-13T03:00:59.348Z","parentId":"17d6d2cf-9069-4819-8506-2d74e8278d53"}
